Given a pair of adjoint functor F \dashv  G, G \mathbin {\circ } F forms a monad. As a converse, we can consider the adjunctions whose composition is a given monad M. These decompositions form a bicategory. The morphisms between two adjunctions are given by functors L that make the two triangles below commute.



            \usepackage{mlmodern, tikz, tikz-cd, quiver, mathtools, amssymb, stmaryrd, mathrsfs}

      \begin {tikzcd}
    {\mathcal {D}_2} & {\mathcal {D}_1} & {\mathcal {C}}
    \arrow [shift right, from=1-2, to=1-3]
    \arrow [shift right, from=1-3, to=1-2]
    \arrow [shift right, curve={height=18pt}, from=1-1, to=1-3]
    \arrow [shift right, curve={height=18pt}, from=1-3, to=1-1]
    \arrow ["L"{description}, from=1-2, to=1-1]
  \end {tikzcd}



  More precisely, the objects of this bicategory are given by adjunctions F \dashv  G together with a natural isomorphism G \mathbin {\circ } F \cong  M. A morphism from F_1 \dashv  G_1 to F_2 \dashv  G_2 is given by a functor L together with two natural isomorphisms L \mathbin {\circ } G_1 \cong  G_2, F_1 \cong  F_2 \mathbin {\circ } L. A 2-morphism is given by a natural transformation such that the relevant composition of natural transformations are equal.

We verify that they form an adjunction. Algebra homomorphisms \varphi : F_M X \to Y are given by commutative squares
\usepackage{mlmodern, tikz, tikz-cd, quiver, mathtools, amssymb, stmaryrd, mathrsfs}
\begin {tikzcd}%tex {M^2 X} & MY \\ MX & Y \arrow["{\alpha_Y}", from=1-2, to=2-2] \arrow["\mu"', from=1-1, to=2-1] \arrow["\varphi", from=2-1, to=2-2] \arrow["{M\varphi}", from=1-1, to=1-2]\end {tikzcd}
while morphisms f : X \to Y fits in the diagram as such:
\usepackage{mlmodern, tikz, tikz-cd, quiver, mathtools, amssymb, stmaryrd, mathrsfs}
\begin {tikzcd}%tex {M^2 X} & MY \\ MX & Y \\ X \arrow["{\alpha_Y}", from=1-2, to=2-2] \arrow["\mu"', from=1-1, to=2-1] \arrow["\varphi", from=2-1, to=2-2] \arrow["{M\varphi}", from=1-1, to=1-2] \arrow["f"', from=3-1, to=2-2] \arrow["\eta", from=3-1, to=2-1] \arrow[from=2-1, to=1-2]\end {tikzcd}
Given a homomorphism \varphi of algebras, we can compute f by composing with \eta . On the other hand, given f, we define \varphi by \alpha _Y \mathbin {\circ } Mf. This creates a commutative square because \begin {aligned} \alpha _Y \mathbin {\circ } M \varphi &= \alpha _Y \mathbin {\circ } M\alpha _Y \mathbin {\circ } M^2 f \\ &= \alpha _Y \mathbin {\circ } \mu \mathbin {\circ } M^2 f \\ &= \alpha _Y \mathbin {\circ } M f \mathbin {\circ } \mu \\ &= \varphi \mathbin {\circ } \mu . \end {aligned}
